{"topicId":"artificial-neurons-perceptron","mcqs":[{"id":"mcq-1","question":"In a single-layer perceptron, what are the three main components of the artificial neuron model?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"Input values, weights, and output function"},{"key":"B","text":"Input values, weights, and activation function"},{"key":"C","text":"Weights, bias, and learning rate"},{"key":"D","text":"Input values, bias, and error function"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"A perceptron consists of input values, weights (including bias), and an activation function that determines the output.","difficulty":"easy"},{"id":"mcq-2","question":"Which of the following is the most commonly used activation function in a basic perceptron that outputs binary values (0 or 1)?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"Sigmoid function"},{"key":"B","text":"ReLU function"},{"key":"C","text":"Step function (Heaviside)"},{"key":"D","text":"Tanh function"}],"correctAnswer":"C","explanation":"The step (Heaviside) function is traditionally used in perceptrons, outputting 1 if net input ≥ 0, else 0.","difficulty":"easy"},{"id":"mcq-3","question":"In the perceptron learning algorithm, how are the weights updated when a misclassification occurs?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"wi(new) = wi(old) + (learning rate × inputi × target)"},{"key":"B","text":"wi(new) = wi(old) + (learning rate × inputi × (target - output))"},{"key":"C","wi(new) = wi(old) × (learning rate × inputi × error)"},{"key":"D","text":"wi(new) = wi(old) - (learning rate × inputi × error)"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"Weights are updated by adding the product of learning rate, input, and the error (target - actual output) to correct misclassifications.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-4","question":"Geometrically, what condition must be satisfied for a perceptron to be able to classify any set of training examples correctly?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"The training examples must be randomly distributed"},{"key":"B","text":"The training examples must be linearly separable by a hyperplane"},{"key":"C","text":"The number of inputs must be greater than the number of outputs"},{"key":"D","text":"The training examples must have equal number of positive and negative samples"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"A perceptron can only classify data that is linearly separable; there must exist a hyperplane that separates the two classes without error.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-5","question":"The Delta rule (also known as the perceptron rule with gradient descent) solves which limitation of the original perceptron learning algorithm?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"It can now solve the XOR problem"},{"key":"B","text":"It works even when data is not linearly separable by using continuous error values"},{"key":"C","text":"It eliminates the need for a bias term"},{"key":"D","text":"It automatically determines the optimal number of neurons"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"The Delta rule uses gradient descent to minimize error, allowing weight adjustment even for non-separable patterns by minimizing the mean squared error.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-6","question":"Why cannot a single-layer perceptron solve the XOR (Exclusive OR) problem?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"XOR requires more than two input nodes"},{"key":"B","text":"XOR outputs are not binary values"},{"key":"C","text":"XOR inputs are not linearly separable in the input space - no single straight line can separate (0,0) and (1,1) from (0,1) and (1,0)"},{"key":"D","text":"The perceptron learning algorithm has a bug when handling XOR inputs"}],"correctAnswer":"C","explanation":"XOR patterns are not linearly separable - there is no hyperplane in 2D input space that can separate the two classes of outputs.","difficulty":"medium"},{"id":"mcq-7","question":"How does a Multi-Layer Perceptron (MLP) overcome the XOR problem that a single-layer perceptron cannot solve?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"By using a different activation function like softmax"},{"key":"B","text":"By introducing hidden layers that create non-linear decision boundaries through composition of functions"},{"key":"C","text":"By increasing the number of output neurons to match input combinations"},{"key":"D","text":"By reducing the learning rate to zero"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"Hidden layers enable the MLP to learn non-linear mappings by composing multiple linear transformations, creating curved decision boundaries.","difficulty":"hard"},{"id":"mcq-8","question":"Consider a perceptron with 3 inputs (x1=1, x2=0, x3=1), weights w1=0.5, w2=-0.5, w3=0.8, and bias b=0.2. Using a step activation function (output=1 if net input ≥ 0, else 0), what is the output?","options":[{"key":"A","text":"0"},{"key":"B","text":"1"},{"key":"C","text":"0.5"},{"key":"D","text":"-0.2"}],"correctAnswer":"B","explanation":"Net input = (1×0.5) + (0×-0.5) + (1×1.8) + 0.2 = 0.5 + 0 + 0.8 + 0.2 = 1.5. Since 1.5 ≥ 0, output = 1.","difficulty":"hard"}]}